Created attachment 4632 Missing scrollbar
Right scrollbar is missing when displaying: https://grok.cz.oracle.com/source/xref/on11u1-clone/usr/src/common/openssl/README.SUNW
The README file is much longer than one screen, and the remainder is not accessible due to the absence of scrollbar.
Browser: FF 8.0
Steps to reproduce: - just view https://grok.cz.oracle.com/source/xref/on11u1-clone/usr/src/common/openssl/README.SUNW
Workaround: - select a specific revision of the file, like: https://grok.cz.oracle.com/source/xref/on11u1-clone/usr/src/common/openssl/README.SUNW?r=8545%3Aa1b3fd5884fd
Please, see attachment.
tried with FF 10.0.2 and couldn't reproduce :(
can you actually force a refresh ? (CTRL+SHIFT+R) it might be css cache specific , I don't see any other obvious cause

Thanks Lubos, it probably was css-cache problem, and force refresh made it go away. Now I feel stupid.
Closing the bug, sorry for the bother...

Well don't feel stupid
since I actually fixed this css cache problem some time ago (in 0.10)
but the web refactoring made the fix go away ... and I was told not to put the code workaround back into the gate ... so ... don't feel like that, since the bug is in firefox and we opengrok doesn't workaround it anymore ...

(In reply to comment #5) > Well > don't feel stupid > > since I actually fixed this css cache problem some time ago (in 0.10) > > but the web refactoring made the fix go away ... > and I was told not to put the code workaround back into the gate ... > so ... don't feel like that, since the bug is in firefox and we opengrok > doesn't workaround it anymore ...
Well, this isn't a caching problem. If the scrollbar does not appear, it is an indicator, that the resizeContent() method wasn't fired (initially via pageReadyMast()) or its execution has been stopped dueto an error ...
Haven't seen this with FF8, FF10, Safari 5.1.2 ...

If the scrollbar does not appear, it is an > indicator, that the resizeContent() method wasn't fired (initially via > pageReadyMast()) or its execution has been stopped dueto an error ... > > Haven't seen this with FF8, FF10, Safari 5.1.2 ...
hmm, then even better ... so this is a bug of firefox then (if I got it correctly) I just tried to reproduce with FF ... seems FF becomes crappy, time to switch to Chrome/Opera ? (and thanks chiming in Jens ;) )

(In reply to comment #7) > (In reply to comment #6) > > (In reply to comment #5) ... > > indicator, that the resizeContent() method wasn't fired (initially via > > pageReadyMast()) or its execution has been stopped dueto an error ... ... > hmm, then even better ... so this is a bug of firefox then (if I got it > correctly) > I just tried to reproduce with FF ... seems FF becomes crappy, time to switch > to Chrome/Opera ?
I don't think, it is an FF problem, but rather a server problem (if this actually happens at all): All pageReady* methods are finally invoked via window.onload (i.e. when all components of the page have been loaded [and thus size calculations are safe]). So if the server doesn't answer a request (e.g. for an inlined image), hangs for some reason or e.g. sends wrong length param (value too big) the browser has to delay the window.onload as well ...
